The question you have to ask is where that fat is. If you're not familiar with basic anatomy, you have three types: subcutaneous (what's under the skin and we usually think about), visceral (part of your gut), and intramuscular.
My anthros in one setting have about 5-7% less body fat than an equivalent human, and I make the point that fur is thermoregulatory in the same way that human subcutaneous fat is.
What defines a muscle's flatness isn't a single factor. It's a mix of hydration, fiber type (which you can't change drastically, but heavy exercise can alter somewhat), and intramuscular fat. Nor is muscle size an indicator of absolute strength.
As for fur...when I've grown out my beard, anything past about 0.5"/12mm makes it impossible to see the shape of my chin. For heavy fur, one inch is a lot of fluff.
So if she's got a flat coat, the combo of low sub-q/high IM fat, and good posture, the answer you want is how observant the narrator is to the small clues.
